It’s been a lifetime of learning this, but in the past few years, it finally clicked. I always try to see the best in people. Even if I see a glimpse of potential or hope, I would filter everything they do and say thru that lens. I would justify their words and behavior based on what I chose to believe instead of what they repeatedly showed to be. Often finding myself disappointed and hurt, with nobody else to blame but myself. 
In any relationship, when engaging with another person, if we take a step back, remove the filters, the projections, and wishful thinking, and pay attention and listen, people will always show and tell us who they are. Usually very early on. 
And when they do, don’t filter or question or doubt or excuse or rationalize. 
Believe them. 
.
.
.
#xhale

Adjust accordingly.

It sounds harsh but it’s true and I hope it fires you up. This was the hardest lesson I had to learn thus far…

When starting any new relationship- work, friendship, dating…Be aware of the dynamics and expectations you set from the beginning. 
It’s easy to point fingers and complain about how others behave and treat you. But when you’re experiencing this, take a step back and take inventory of what’s the behavior you have been tolerating and what are the boundaries (if any) you set, and then take full responsibility for your part in why this is happening. 
It’s never too late to course correct, but be prepared for resistance or even complete termination of the relationship. Nobody likes their perks taken away from them. But if they care about you, they will adopt.
Now, it’s a different story when you do set boundaries and express your needs, and those are continuously being violated or not met. Then the best thing to do is to walk away quietly. 
.
.
#accountability
